const MDXLayout = "wrapper"
export default function MDXContent({
  components,
  ...props
}) {
  return <MDXLayout {...layoutProps} {...props} components={components} mdxType="MDXLayout">

    <p>{`Vector now supports `}<a parentName="p" {...{
        "href": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ARM_architecture"
      }}>{`ARM architectures`}</a>{` on the Linux platform! These
architectures are widely used in embeded devices and recently started to get
traction on servers. To get started, you can follow the installation
instructions for your preferred method:`}</p>
    <ul>
      <li parentName="ul"><a parentName="li" {...{
          "href": "/docs/setup/installation/package-managers/dpkg/"
        }}>{`DPKG`}</a>{` (select the ARM tab)`}</li>
      <li parentName="ul"><a parentName="li" {...{
          "href": "/docs/setup/installation/package-managers/rpm/"
        }}>{`RPM`}</a>{` (select the ARM tab)`}</li>
      <li parentName="ul"><a parentName="li" {...{
          "href": "/docs/setup/installation/platforms/docker/"
        }}>{`Docker`}</a>{` (select the ARM tab)`}</li>
      <li parentName="ul"><a parentName="li" {...{
          "href": "/docs/setup/installation/manual/from-archives/"
        }}>{`From archives`}</a></li>
      <li parentName="ul"><a parentName="li" {...{
          "href": "/releases/"
        }}>{`Or, download the files directly`}</a></li>
    </ul>
    {
      /*truncate*/
    }
    <h2 {...{
      "id": "fully-static-without-dependencies"
    }}>{`Fully-static without dependencies`}</h2>
    <p>{`It's worth noting that Vector ships a fully static binary without dependencies.
This makes installation as simple as copying the Vector binary onto
your machine. There are no dependencies to install or environment changes
required.`}</p>
    <h2 {...{
      "id": "dpkg-rpm--docker-support"
    }}>{`DPKG, RPM, & Docker support`}</h2>
    <p>{`In addition to providing archives for these architectures, we went the extra
mile to ensure `}<a parentName="p" {...{
        "href": "/docs/setup/installation/package-managers/dpkg/"
      }}>{`DPKG`}</a>{`,
`}<a parentName="p" {...{
        "href": "/docs/setup/installation/package-managers/rpm/"
      }}>{`RPM`}</a>{`, and `}<a parentName="p" {...{
        "href": "/docs/setup/installation/platforms/docker/"
      }}>{`Docker`}</a>{` support
them as well.`}</p>
    <h2 {...{
      "id": "usecases"
    }}>{`Usecases`}</h2>
    <p>{`If you're wondering how this benefits you, here are a couple of popular use
cases:`}</p>
    <h3 {...{
      "id": "aws-performance-improvements-and-cost-savings"
    }}>{`AWS performance improvements and cost savings`}</h3>
    <p>{`An interesting usecase for ARM support are the `}<a parentName="p" {...{
        "href": "https://aws.amazon.com/about-aws/whats-new/2019/12/announcing-new-amazon-ec2-m6g-c6g-and-r6g-instances-powered-by-next-generation-arm-based-aws-graviton2-processors/"
      }}>{`new AWS `}<inlineCode parentName="a">{`M6g`}</inlineCode>{`, `}<inlineCode parentName="a">{`C6g`}</inlineCode>{`, and `}<inlineCode parentName="a">{`R6g`}</inlineCode>{`
instances`}</a>{`. These instances are based on Amazon's
ARM-based Graviton2 processors. Amazon claims they "deliver up to 40% improved
price/performance over current generation `}<inlineCode parentName="p">{`M5`}</inlineCode>{`, `}<inlineCode parentName="p">{`C5`}</inlineCode>{`, and `}<inlineCode parentName="p">{`R5`}</inlineCode>{` instances".`}</p>
    <h3 {...{
      "id": "raspbian-iot--embedded-devices"
    }}>{`Raspbian, IoT, & embedded devices`}</h3>
    <p>{`ARM architectures are widely used on IoT devices. Vector is the perfect
candidate for resource constrainted environments like this, especially given
`}<a parentName="p" {...{
        "href": "/#performance"
      }}>{`Vector's superior memory efficiency`}</a>{`.`}</p>
    <h2 {...{
      "id": "the-case-for-vector"
    }}>{`The case for Vector`}</h2>
    <p>{`If you're using a vendor-based data collector it's likely they lack support
for the ARM architectures, especially the new ARM64 architecture. This limits
your flexibility, and in the case of AWS, can have direct cost implications.
Supporting these platforms, properly, is Vector's core competency.`}</p>
    </MDXLayout>;
}

